Style choices that age well.

Opinions you will thank yourself for in two years.

Small functions. A function that fits on a screen is debuggable. A function that does not is not. Split aggressively.

Explicit data. Pass dictionaries, data-classes, named-tuples — not the third positional argument is the count. Type hints make this concrete.

Pure when you can. A function that does not mutate its inputs and does not read global state is testable and composable. Reach for mutation only when you have decided you need it.

Hard-to-misuse application programming interfaces. Keyword-only flags, default arguments that fail loud when wrong, names that say what they mean — timeout-seconds, not just timeout. The reader of your code in six months is yourself with no memory of the conversation that led to this design.

Comments explain why, not what. The code says what. The comment says why it is that way and not the other way.

Tests as the second documentation. A failing test pins down what was promised. A passing test demonstrates how the application programming interface is meant to be used. Notebook ten covers py-test.
